# Optional: TTS (text-to-speech) — enables the speaker button in the output and source panels.
# Point at any OpenAI-compatible /v1/audio/speech endpoint.
# Recommended for self-hosted TTS: speaches-ai (https://speaches.ai) with the
# Kokoro-82M-v1.0-ONNX model, which natively supports en, es, fr, hi, it, ja, pt, zh.
# All other languages (de, nl, pl, ru, ko, ar, ...) fall back to TTS_VOICE.
# TTS_API_BASE_URL is the base URL of the TTS endpoint (no trailing slash).
# TTS_MODEL: model ID your endpoint expects.
# TTS_VOICE: default voice — used for languages not in TTS_VOICE_MAP.
# TTS_CHUNK_SIZE: max bytes per synthesis request.
#   0 / unset = no chunking (single request per TTS call).
#   Set to 4000 to match the OpenAI hosted-API limit.
#   Note: Japanese TTS quality issues in speaches-ai are caused by espeak switching
#   phoneme sets mid-utterance ("language switches" warning). This is an espeak/
#   speaches-ai limitation that chunking does not fix; it requires a native Japanese
#   phonemizer (pyopenjtalk/MeCab) to be used upstream.
# TTS_VOICE_MAP: per-language voice overrides — comma-separated lang:voice pairs.
#   The frontend sends ISO 639-1 codes (en, fr, ja, zh, ...) as the language key.
#   Each value can optionally include a model override using "voice@model" notation,
#   e.g. "af_heart@gpgpu/speaches-tts". When present the model suffix is used as
#   the "model" field in the API request, overriding TTS_MODEL for that language.
#   This is useful when the TTS endpoint is a gateway that maps model IDs to backends
#   (e.g. "gpgpu/speaches-tts" → speaches-ai service).
